## вњЁ Features

- рџЊЎпёЏ Measures temperature and humidity using a BME280 sensor  
- рџ–ҐпёЏ Displays live data on an SSD1306 OLED screen (128x64)  
- рџ“¶ Creates its own WiFi hotspot (`MijnESP32`)  
- рџЊђ Local web server at `http://192.168.4.1`  
- в™»пёЏ Auto-refreshes every 2 seconds (via JavaScript)  
- вљ пёЏ Error handling for sensor failures or loose connections  
- рџ”’ No sensitive data in main code.  
- рџ§  Non-blocking timing with `millis()` в†’ web server stays responsive
- рџЊЎпёЏ Smart alert system: Reacts to high temperature with LED, OLED, and web feedback. 

---

> вљ пёЏ **Why no `В°` symbol?**  
> The `Adafruit_SSD1306` library has limited support for special characters like the degree symbol (`В°`). To keep the code simple and reliable for beginners, the OLED displays only `"C"` instead of `"В°C"`.  
>   
> вњ… The **web version** (in your browser) **does show** the correct `В°C` symbol thanks to HTML encoding.

This is a common limitation in embedded displays вЂ” not a bug!

## рџ§° Components Required

- ESP32 Development Board (e.g., ESP32 DevKit)
- BME280 temperature/humidity sensor (IВІC)
- SSD1306 OLED display (128x64, IВІC)
- Breadboard and jumper wires
- Micro-USB cable
- RED LED
- 2x 220 Ohm Resistor
- 1x pushbutton

---

## рџ”Њ Wiring (IВІC Bus)

Both sensors share the same IВІC pins (button added):

| ESP32 Pin | Function | Connected To        |
|----------|----------|--------------------- |
| 3.3V     | Power    | VCC of BME280 + OLED |
| GND      | Ground   | GND of BME280 + OLED + Button(one side) |
| GPIO21   | SDA      | SDA of BME280 + OLED |
| GPIO22   | SCL      | SCL of BME280 + OLED |
| GPIO4    | Input    | Button(other side)   |

Note: The button is connected between GPIO 4 and GND. The code enables the internal pull-up resistor, so no external resistor is required.


> рџ’Ў Ensure both devices use **different IВІC addresses** (BME280: `0x76`, OLED: `0x3C`).

---

## в–¶пёЏ Usage

1. **Install required libraries** in Arduino IDE:  
   - `Adafruit BME280 Library`  
   - `Adafruit SSD1306`  
   - `Adafruit GFX Library`

> 2. Create `secrets.h` by copying `secrets.h.example` to `secrets.h`, then edit the values:
> ```bash
> cp secrets.h.example secrets.h
> ```

> Open `secrets.h` and replace `"MijnESP32"` and `"12345678"` with your WiFi name and password.
